{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014eBZZWbndm62Fs3nFg3da4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. I can see the namespace exists with:\n- Two helper pods already running: `curl-test` and `openssl-toolbox`\n- The `elastic-password` secret and `es-http-tls` secret exist\n\nNow I need to deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources. Let me check the TLS secret to understand what's in it.\n\nLet me plan the deployment:\n1. A ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. A headless Service for pod-to-pod communication (es-internal)\n3. A Service named `es-http` for client access\n4. A StatefulSet for the 3 Elasticsearch nodes\n5. A PodDisruptionBudget\n\nFor Elasticsearch 8.x, security is enabled by default with HTTPS and authentication required. I have the `es-http-tls` secret containing the certificate, key, and CA certificate, plus the `elastic-password` secret. I need to configure TLS for both HTTP and inter-node transport communication, potentially reusing the HTTP TLS certificate for transport or setting up separate transport TLS.\n\nFor a native Kubernetes deployment, I'll need to configure the `elasticsearch.yml` file, mount the TLS secrets as volumes, and set appropriate environment variables. Since I only have one TLS secret available, I can use the same certificate for both HTTP and transport communication by setting the verification mode to only check the certificate chain rather than requiring exact hostname matches.\n\nConfiguring the elasticsearch.yml... The node names need to align with the StatefulSet pod naming convention—with a StatefulSet named `es`, the pods will be `es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2`, so I should set `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to those exact names. For discovery, I can point `discovery.seed_hosts` to the headless service name `es-internal` to let the nodes find each other. I'm setting resource requests and limits for each node—1GB memory and 500m CPU as requests, with 2GB and 1 CPU as limits, plus configuring the JVM heap to 1GB. I need to pull the Elasticsearch password from a secret via environment variable, then I'll write out the full YAML manifest with the ConfigMap, headless service for discovery, HTTP service, PodDisruptionBudget, and StatefulSet with three replicas.\n\nWriting Kubernetes manifests... Writing Elasticsearch config... Configuring the StatefulSet with three Elasticsearch replicas, setting up an init container to fix data directory permissions, and defining the main Elasticsearch container with the appropriate image and environment variables. Finishing the readiness probe with a curl command that checks the cluster health status, then defining the volumes for the config and certificates, and setting up a persistent volume claim template requesting 10Gi of storage. I'm noticing some concerns about whether a default storage class exists and whether the memory limits are appropriate for the workload.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":460,"cache_read_input_tokens":28242,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":460},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e75b3fab-749e-4aeb-968c-fec95891c9a6","uuid":"51aa3c8c-8974-407c-96d1-9ded6e4fa2f9","request_id":"req_011Cc8tMUtX9iJHH7yQy5kGH"}
